Thermosynechococcus elongatus
Thermosynechococcus elongatus is one of the model organisms used for investigating photosynthesis
Thermosynechococcus elongatus has long been used as a model organism for investigating photosynthesis.
It is a thermophilic unicellular rod shaped cyanobacterium, the organism lives in hot springs and has an optimum growth temperature of 55C.
The sequenced strain was isolated from Beppu hot spring in Japan.
Cyanobacteria is a general term for bacteria capable of oxygenic photosyntheses, which comprises over 1500 species.


